You’ll need an encoder and a PID controller to make the elevator move smoothly and stop correctly at each level. The encoder keeps track of the motor’s position and speed, and the PID controller uses this information to adjust the motor’s movement. This way, the elevator will stop exactly where it should.

You can explore the WPILib website for more examples.

Hardware-wise, all you’ll need is a motor/motor controller, and an encoder. If you are using a SparkMAX → NEO v1.1, I know for a fact that those have built-in encoders. It would be a good idea to have a limit switch on the robot, but not technically needed.

Software-wise, you need a way to view the encoder values on Smart Dashboard/shuffleboard. A PID controller would be nice, but not technically needed. You could just send power to the motors, hit a certain amount of encoder ticks, and stop sending power.

A good example of code to use as a jumping point would be Team 904’s 2023 robot code. While I do believe it is now outdated, there are examples of working code on how to do it (btw the code isn’t very pretty but it does work, at least it did).

In addition to what others have said, regarding motors, encoders, etc…

Elevators need a feedback controller and usually feedforward as well. Feedforward, in this case, means two things: some constant voltage applied to the motors to hold against gravity, and extra voltage applied to achieve acceleration and desired velocity as the elevator moves. Read this section (from PID Control in WPILib to Combining Motion Profiling and PID Control with ProfiledPIDController). Also, read through this section and try your hand at tuning the various systems.

Some sample code for a simulated elevator (which could be adapted into controlling a real one):

github.com

CommandElevatorSimulation/src/main/java/frc/robot at main ·...

An adaptation and expansion of the WPILib Elevator Simulation into a Command-based version - FRCTeam695/CommandElevatorSimulation

Some videos on the base this simulation comes from:

Getting Started

What the stuff inside means

The most critical thing to getting an elevator running and tuned is to have a good view of your important variables. You want to see a plots of desired versus achieved values: position AND velocity. You also want to be able to see the different terms contributing to control effort: voltage due to feedforward, proportional control, etc…

General order of steps I recommend:

  • choose your motor (ideally brushless with encoder)
  • choose gear ratios (use https://Reca.lc or similar)
  • design and build the elevator
  • set up plots of the important variables
  • establish that the encoder does indeed work; determine max travel by moving the elevator with the robot disabled
  • configure soft limits (i.e., don’t apply power if it would try to force against the hard limits)
  • run elevator manually (controller sets voltage); make sure it works
  • configure 2 buttons for 2 setpoints
  • create a way to set tuning constants with Glass or another dashboard
  • tune elevator feedforward constants (kS, kG, kV, kA)
  • tune feedback controller (kP, kD if needed, kI only if all else fails)
  • create additional setpoints as needed

My favorite homing system is “put it at the bottom and press a button”.
